metadata.name: Life has no scores #104
metadata.description:
We cannot compose life, at best we hum along to the melodies that life has been played in front of us. Looking back at the scores of our lives, the notations are never neatly noted, but fully felt.  Rewinding the songs of life are our memories, whether sad, happy, angry, or melancholy. It is not clear whether I am dreaming or awake, but our songs all do end. 

In this final drop (for ?), I have reused the first ever class calligraphy(){} I have written from my genesis drop “Nothing comes from nothing”. As time passes, 10 drops later, across almost to the year, I am grateful for the progress I have made, as an artist, and more importantly as a human. After all, what is behind the code of generative art is a human being. 

Scores of music, scrolls of calligraphy, calendar or diary, notating life, time passes, and changes are inevitable. Sometimes we sing louder in laughter and joy, sometimes we scribble in uneasiness, sometimes we just get lost in neon lights. Life goes on. You and me, all the same and yet different.  

There are too many friend artists, friend collectors, fxhash team members, to thank for helping me through this journey. I would like to pay homage to Rudxane in this work, who has taken me under his wings, mentoring and encouraging me in art as well as showing me some degen stuff on the side:-). This homage is not copy-minting, or copying of styles, which I do not have the coding skills to do so even if I wanted to. But it is the influence of taste in many works of Rudxane. In a vague but agreeable taste, I present to you Life has no scores. 

What I was taught was disrupted, and grid studies left unfinished, and oh do we have a BINGO?

Tested on Chrome. Other browsers may render different or not at all (firefox)

Press ‘2’ to save png.

metadata.name: Agora of Timeless #44
metadata.description:
While talking about Socrates,Bonnard gives a general description of the people and life in the agora:
 “On an ordinary day, the local square is full of people. Butchers selling pork sausages, praise the product, the cavalry officer hand to hoop the woman selling kipper fish. In front of the barber house, the money changers, all the Athenian jaws around their table are talking, and Socrates passes from the agora. Everyone knows him".
 Andre Boonard

My starting point in this collection is to make the audience feel a connection with an architectural composition I aimed. That's why firstly I created a composition, has a 360-degree view in the square of an ancient city. There are rules of the physical world; I designed it with elements such as atmosphere and movement, far-near relationship, texture. I aimed to strengthen the depth by using obelisks, stone walls, arches and icons from ancient objects in space composition.

It was published in my detailed article about this collection.

* Each composition has its own unique 360-degree view.
You can activate the 360 ​​view by pressing the “Q” key.

* 2d and 3d images of each composition have rain feature.
You can activate the rain mode by pressing the "E" key.

* Save image: press 'W' to save the current image as png.

--------------------------------------------------------------
* 15 percent of the royalty will belong to the minters.

* According to my period, the owners of “Stratification of the Orthogonal”, “Agora of Timeless” and incoming project will have free mint rights of the next project.

metadata.name: Warped #90
metadata.description:
A free little toy.  Play with it and it might make art!  This is my second project using a shader.  It starts by making a simple drawing, then the shader uses noise to warp the image.  I'm making it free because 1) You really have to work at it to make art (but I think it's a lot of fun to tinker with!), and 2) the capture sometimes has minor variances from the final image - couldn't figure it out.  Made with p5js and uses some Perlin noise code by Inigo Quilez.  

After opening, press "s" to save a large jpg.

metadata.name: Element #161
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: NESTED IDENTITIES #172
metadata.description:
Nested identities redact fingerprints but deeper meaning can still be found.

Nested identifies refers to the idea that a person may have multiple identities that are interconnected and interdependent. These identities may be related to a person's cultural background, ethnicity, nationality, gender, sexual orientation, social class, profession, and other factors. It is possible that a person may want to conceal or redact certain aspects of their identity in order to protect their privacy or to avoid discrimination or persecution. However, even if certain details about a person's identity are hidden or redacted, it may still be possible to infer deeper meaning or understand more about their experiences and perspectives based on the context in which they express themselves and the information that is available.


The concept of nested identities highlights the complexity and multifaceted nature of a person's identity, and how different aspects of identity can intersect and influence each other. It is important to recognize and respect the diversity of identities that people may hold, and to be mindful of the ways in which power dynamics and social context can shape how people present and express their identities. It is also important to recognize that people's identities may evolve and change over time, and that everyone has the right to self-identify and to define their own identity on their own terms.

Press p to download a high quality export.

metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #96
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: CELDAS #255
metadata.description:
Cells, called "CELDAS" in Spanish, are spaces separated by lines or stripes in a geometric structure. Generally, cells are formed when the stripes intersect to form a mesh or grid. Each cell formed by these stripes can be filled with a color to create a design.
I love the way I can play with the horizontality and verticality of the stripes to create unique and original geometric patterns, and how through different sizes of stripes an infinity of pieces are formed ranging from the minimalist and sophisticated to the most colorful and expressive, bringing each piece a fresh and current air within a vibrant color palette.
The DNA of this collection is my passion for stripes and colors, both united in a single project that reflects my love in each piece.
I hope you enjoy it as much as I do!
